text: Here's what I'll say, as a Hellboy fan. This is fine, but it feels like it lacks the heart of the Del Toro's (just going off what I see here.)  Del Toro's movies were such a labor of love. He was underfunded on both movies and they outperformed even what the studios expected. Yet, they were more inclined to not pay the guy to finish the trilogy like they had originally intended.  I'm just not sold on a new director/movie. They don't have the love or devotion to monsters like he does. I know they want a franchise, but they could of had it before and opted out. Harbour's practical makeup and prosthetics look terrible and out of place against the CG. It just doesn't gel as well as Del Toro's reliance on mostly practical effects and limited CG, making for a more whimsical, yet horrifying product. That's something rarely created in this franchise driven world. It could of set itself apart from the machine made art hitting shelves now.  A mild disclaimer, though, The Golden Army is one of my all time favorite movies, so I'm probably a little bias, but still, I think I make a lot of sense here.

text: So Lionsgate owns these movies? Does that prevent Hellboy from being in DC movies in the future, unless they do a loan a la Spider-Man?  With people somehow seeing Wonder Woman as a good movie and that mass delusion resulting in a hit, Aquaman seeming like it actually is as good as a kid friendly hero movie can be, as well as Shazam! looking decent in the same sense and now this looking to be at least as good as any of the non-Russo Brothers Marvel crap everyone seemed to enjoy....   DC may actually be able to remove the terrible, terrible, terrible, terrible, awful, terrible shit pile that Hack Snyder left behind and have a decent franchise going forward.  Losing Cavill as Superman though... That's a really big blow for this hope. He was the perfect Superman... Squandered by a moron that who ZERO business deciding the overall plot.   I like a lot of his ideas when it comes to various little details, like Batmans voice modulator, the choice of allowing him to be violent in taking out killers... Shit like that. He had a good sense of what would be cool and badass.   And he is a terrific cinematographer.. absolutely outstanding.  But the guy was a moron who didn't get what makes movies good and interesting. He had no clue about what things to focus on. Superman and Batman are about more than action scenes and punching. You gotta hype up every single thing each hero does in a compelling way. Every punch and kick should have emotional weight behind it.  He did next to nothing to hype Superman up. I mean in the sense of him being the greatest blessing to the Earth that it could ever possibly get. A symbol of hope AND an AGENT of hope.There was ONE scene that sorta did this and it was a throwaway montage with no real emotional context  The scene where he saves the poor woman, weeping from overwhelming gratitude when she was sure she and her family were dead... This regular man with power to answer the most desperate of prayers... THAT is how you focus on Superman. Not have him be a stylish action hero. Hack Snyder completely missed the point of Superman.   Hack... Snyder. Sickens me that people who don't get it are the ones who get to write these movies. I could literally write a better movie by the end of the day. Literally. Well, I'd have the treatment done. Detailed dialogue and pacing would take a couple weeks at most. The shit writes itself. It sickens me.  Now they gotta recast Superman and Batman, while other characters are successful hits... And they gotta pretend JL didn't happen? Or what? Continuity just wrecked. Sickens me.

text: This looks really mediocre. This is the polar opposite of Guillermo Del Toro‚Äôs Hellboy movies, and that‚Äôs not a good thing. I don‚Äôt know why they‚Äôre making this a comedy when it just won‚Äôt work as a straight up comedy. Comedic elements would be fine, though. The Hellboy costume looks ugly and somehow worse than the costume used a decade ago. I like David Harbour, I think he‚Äôs a good actor, but he does not fit this role. He obviously doesn‚Äôt have the charm and personality that Ron Perlman brought to the table. This movie‚Äôs special effects somehow look worse than ‚ÄòThe Golden Army‚Äô, a DECADE OLD MOVIE. But here‚Äôs the kicker, I not only don‚Äôt mind the gore, but I think it was a good choice along with the R-rating. I don‚Äôt think Hellboy should be saying ‚Äòfuck‚Äô every other word, which I assume they‚Äôre going to do because they want to be EDGY and COOL and they want to exercise that R-rating and be just like Deadpool. This trailer makes the movie look really mediocre (at best) but I really hope they can recapture some of Guillermo‚Äôs magic and make this at least ‚Äògood‚Äô.

text: They couldn't have given it a subtitle? Just calling it Hellboy is kinda dumb when we already have a movie just called Hellboy. And a damn good movie at that. I haven't seen a lot of Stanger Things so I can't judge David Harbour on what I've seen in other stuff. But just based on this trailer, he doesn't hold a candle to Ron Perlman. I do love Ian McShane though, an great casting choice there. Also, 1:40 I spy Kroenen, which is awesome. Creatively though, it seems very generic when compared to Del Toro's movies. The monsters designs seem boring (expect for that thing, 1:32, that looks pretty cool) and all CG. And, it seems to be going the Guardians/Suicide Squad route in terms of tone (at least the trailer is), and while I love Guardians of the Galaxy, I don't want every superhero movie to just copy what they did.

text: If you are willing to sit down and examine the trailer its really not all that bad. Just put YouTube speed on 0.25, mute your volume and it has some really great hidden moments within it. I have listed a few ‚ÄúKey Moments‚Äù for you slackers ;)  but first my thoughts on the trailer‚Ä¶.  Overall I believe the tone of the trailer is playful and comedic. I think that it destroys and distracts from what the film truly is. A dark, gritty, bad ass movie that was made for a mature audience. My guess for the comedic/ ‚Äúlight hearted‚Äù tone that is presented was intentionally done as a marketing strategy.( It‚Äôs failing miserably) They did this in fear that a dark superhero can‚Äôt survive in todays ever growing Marvel and Dc trite. Therefore we are left with the cast and directors telling us its going to be this horror-action film during interviews, then we have Lionsgate come along and promote it as‚Ä¶.well in the ‚ÄúLegendary AF‚Äù movie-thingy-cabob style. That is conflicting with what the film actually is, but with some recent marketing images/ leaked early viewer reviews, I am beginning to see a ‚Äúcourse correction‚Äù. In the end, I will ABSOLUTELY see this movie. Just from a fan‚Äôs perspective I want to see the Hellboy franchise succeed and something tells me that if this movie fails we won‚Äôt be seeing Hellboy on the big screen for at least another decade, maybe longer‚Ä¶‚Ä¶      At 0:14 Excalibur (the sword is still in the stone) I see what they did there   At 1:05 Hellboy possibly picking up The Good Samaritan?   At 1:27 This is definitely a scene that adapts story elements from the comic B.P.R.D Hell On Earth and or Rasputin The Voice Of The Dragon  At 1:28 We get a glimpse at this strange bat like creature. Well, in the comics Hellboy fights a professional wrestler that turns into a vampire. This is again a fantastic adaptation from comic to screen  At 1:39   (This is probably a flashback) You can see Grigori Rasputin performing the ritual to open the portal. He appears to be a direct adaptation from the comic pages to the big screen. Which we all know will lead to the ‚Äúbirth‚Äù of Hellboy. Something to note * he doesn‚Äôt have his signature glove* Another key figure in this scene is Karl Ruprecht Kroenen.   At 1:43 Hellboy is fighting on a group of Giants. Possible Hellboy: Wild Hunt story element? In the comic he was able to kill six giants.   At 1:54  We get to see Ben Daimio as the WereJaguar! Its really fast and blurry though. From what I can tell he is NOT crimson in color. The overall design is very reminiscent of the US Being Human werewolf‚Ä¶.still can‚Äôt judge until I have seen more. Just keep this in mind   At 2:04 Hellboy emerges from some kind of pit? Full on ‚ÄúBeast of The Apocalypse‚Äù flaming crown, horns and a flaming excalibur‚Ä¶.so cool, just so cool   Last but not least some random stuff‚Ä¶  Hellboy‚Äôs hairline recedes when his horns grown and the crown is visible‚Ä¶..interesting?  Gruagach appears more than one time throughout this trailer.(duh) Considering David Harbour is 6‚Äô3, Gruagach is probably 8 to 9 ft tall in this adaptation. Also that scene when the old woman is shooting at the front of the store....and its a secret base......Captain America: The First Avenger anyone? I doubt that was the intention I'm just saying   *** I got to put this in here because surely someone will try to call me out for some reason, I‚Äôm just a fan, whether you agree with me or not is up to you. I‚Äôm just sharing my thoughts like everyone else, except the difference is I‚Äôm not going to throw a fit if the trailer didn‚Äôt meet my expectations. I also missed A LOT I am sure but I just gave some acknowledgment to the fact that this is more than likely a good movie and I wish it the best!***

text: I don't understand the need to make a trailer full of jokes that are not even funny to promote a movie based on a work that is dark and lovecraftian. I mean, Hellboy has humor but its dark, the world Mignola created is so dense with esoteric references, old dilapidated ruins and myths that makes this trailer look like the people that made it didn't even read an issue of the original comic. And I get that this is a different medium and that directors have their own visions and all that jazz, but if you are going to change the original material so much, why even make a movie based on it? Maybe this is just an unfortunate trailer, a la battlefield V reveal, but if the entire movie is like this it's going to piss off a lot of people.  How do you make a movie about Hellboy where Hellboy doesn't look like himself?

text: Not the strongest first impression, but I'm not declaring all hope lost on this movie either. I thought it was a bad idea to introduce this new version of Hellboy with a gag, and the trailer as a whole leans a bit too hard on the comedy in my opinion, but a lot of the tone seems to be coming from the editing and music of the trailer, and those comic scenes might be a minority in the actual film. I saw a few shots that gave me a touch of that Mike Mignola magic, so maybe the finished project is a lot more Hellboy-ish than this trailer tells us. Obviously, I could be dead wrong, and this movie buries the Hellboy franchise outside of comics, but for now, I'm gonna try to be cautiously optimistic.

text: Ummmmmmm...  Hellboy (2004) cost $66 million. Hellboy II: The Golden Army cost $85 million.   Mike Mignola said he wanted a reboot that was R-rated and closer in tone and spirit to the comics. So... he seriously made a movie that apparently feels exactly like del Toro's Hellboy for presumably somewhere in the $66-$85 million range instead of just making Hellboy III!?    Del Toro sat down with Mignola and the studio in February 2017 about making Hellboy III next after The Shape of the Water (this was right after he put a poll up on Twitter on February 18th asking whether fans still wanted it). On February 21st del Toro announced Hellboy III will never happen and he was moving on. On March 8th, Mignola announced an R-rated Hellboy reboot that was closer in tone and spirit to the comics.    I had made peace with the fact that I'd never get Hellboy III and was actually really looking forward to this darker reboot. I like Neil Marshall. I like David Harbour. Let's do this. Today we get a trailer for a Hellboy reboot that's far more del Toro than Mignola. I'm so fucking pissed right now.    Either make a darker, more comics accurate Hellboy movie (which I was cool with), or just spend the same fucking amount of money on del Toro's Hellboy III. Instead they went with "Door Number 3", which is fucking pointless.

text: To all the guys who are crying over the new Hellboy movie: rethink your attitude. You expect from the Hellboy comic flick to be a complete Guillermo Del Toro visionary - in parts grotesque - tale, which it doesn't even try to be and doesn't need to. The original movie was alright: it had nice characters, solid fights and eye-catching colour tones. But the sequel, entitled "The Golden Army", was such a money grab, such a messy tasteless pile of crap that it could even compete with Michael Bay's recent 'Transformers' entries. What I'm trying to say is don't push on this movie too hard for trying to be as funny as 'Thor: Ragnarok' or 'Deadpool'. First, let it come out, then watch it, and only then judge - by rights and not (I don't care).  By the way, seems like the director has got a better idea of embodying the main character than Del Toro himself. David Harbour seems a top-notch Hellboy, I must say!

text: I hope to god that the movie is darker than this trailer makes it seem, I still have very high hopes considering it‚Äôs rated R.  The comics balanced dark and humor so well and I was hoping that could be recreated here but the directors went on record saying this would be darker than the original Hellboy movies and (from this trailer) it looks so... goofy. Goofier than the other movies and in no way dark. Again, I have really high hopes because it‚Äôs rated R and because this is just a short trailer that most likely consists of just ‚Äúfunny‚Äù parts but still.  Do it right, I beg of you. I‚Äôm also trying not to let nostalgia change my view or opinions but come on, Ron Pearlman fit Hellboy so well with his voice, his attitude and everything else. This just seems off. It‚Äôs the nostalgia talking, I know, but again, come on.  EDIT: I don‚Äôt really know what I‚Äôm trying to say, I might just be getting to worked up and if you think that I‚Äôm sorry. text: My opinion on the original 2 and this trailer. Hellboy 1 & 2 were interesting and visually astonishing for its time and even to this day. But as films they both really sucked ass. I remembered them being fun and cool and when rewatching the 2 I could barely sit through them. Ron Perlman with his voice and attitude held those movies on his back without a doubt.  I love David Habor and I think he'll do a great job as he does with just about any role he takes on but I think I speak for many people when I say nobody was ready for this trailer. It lacks the things we've grown to enjoy with a cinematic hellboy. I think it will stay true to the comicbook fans for many of reasons but I worry that this movie will be a movie you can't wait to finish watching. I'm also not a fan of the cast members with the exception of Habor & McShane.  I'm still going to see it in theatres regardless!

text: Wait... so ... at first I thought this was a continuation off of Guillermo del Toro's Hellboy movies... Man I'm sorry but this looks cheesy AF and the makeup/effects look years behind the 2004 movies!!!  ...::scratches head::  I don't know what people define as "DARK" these days but holy sh!t I must be desensitized as fvck because nothing they make anymore is "Dark."  This comes across wonky and goofy.  Why remake the 2004 Hellboy?  It wasn't broken - it was fan-fvcking-tastic. text: Oh, ok, now it looks like something from the Marvel Studios. Worse, it looks like DCU trying to be Marvel Studios.  Bad Jokes Bad CGI (ok, it's not bad, but it's all over the place and we can feel how fake it looks)  As much as I liked  Del Toro's movies, my grip with them is that they were kinda just ok: despite everything, the plot, the villains, part of the dialogues and even the action itself felt like just another Action flick go-to. I thought this would fix it. But no.  It seems even MORE driven into action flicks go-to, but without the good bits of Del Toro's: the amazing visuals, practical effects and smart jokes.  And honestly? You are going to show Nimue on a live-action and she looks THIS BASIC?

text: I get the sense that this is trying to showcase the movie in a more widely appealing way than they had originally described. From a lot of the shots, I definitely feel that it could emulate the darker essence of the comics, but I'd be willing to bet that they want it to draw in some of the moviegoers who have become hooked on current superhero movies like Deadpool and MCU films.  On another note, I am eager to see how David Harbour does in this role. Ron Perlman will always be the face and voice of Hellboy for me, but just as Sean Connery's excellent performance of James Bond in the first films didn't discredit later actors for the character, I feel that David could pull off something really nice for this movie. I know how it sounds, but even before I knew about him being cast as Hellboy, I watched him on Stranger Things and thought to myself "This guy would make a good Hellboy."

Like you have true comic book  fans, then you have true Hollywood fans, then you have just movie goers who most of the time don‚Äôt know what they are seeing before they get into the theater. So when you mix comics with Hollywood blockbuster action, it‚Äôs not going to look good on screen. I love David Harbour but man does this look bad. They should‚Äôve just made a 3rd Hellboy.... text: I don't get it. I love Hellboy, both of Guillermo's movies and the comics. I'm actually quite hyped for this movie, even if the trailer is going a bit too lighthearted, leans WAY too hard on that song. You can have a dark movie that has a lighthearted bits- like Guillermo's Hellboy. Like Evil Dead 2. Like Zombieland. And the comics are darker, but no different. There's literally a part where Abe and HB take on a monkey with a gun, plus the line "Don't mess with me lady, I've been drinking with skeletons" always got a smirk out of me. I'm sad there's no Abe, he should DEFINITELY be here, but I'm still looking forward to this. Plus it's great to see him just out in the open, he was never quite as secretive in the comics as he was in Guillermo's films.  So what's everyone's problem? Just wait for the next trailer, or the movie itself. Or just don't watch it, Guillermo's movies and the comics aren't gonna magically disappear.  Also, I LOVE Ron Pearlman's Hellboy, but Aarbour's looks sick. The only problem I had was the face, but then I looked closer. It's scarred. Scars litter his body, and ESPECIALLY his face. This makes some sense, the dude gets into some nasty fights regularly. Plus there's something about that smirk 1:01 that I adore. Ron looks like Hellboy straight out of the comics. David looks like a fucking DEMON, especially here 2:06 where he even bares his teeth like a beast. Which, again, makes sense. Hellboy is meant to be an intimidating badass with a heart of gold, and I'm sold on that here.  And is NO ONE gonna mention the Baba Yaga's house? Or that we get Hecate played by an actress that was probably DYING for a change of pace?

text: For people dissing the makeup and prattling about range of emotion:  Watch the clip where he says ‚ÄúYou made me a damn weapon‚Äù, then try to remember this trailer is collection of short clips from quite some distance away from the character.  For both people hating that it‚Äôs not Ron Perlman and people wishing he was less like Ron Perlman:  Ask yourselves, how can a movie appeal to both your predilections? Let me help... it can‚Äôt   For those who are boycotting it immediately for simply using a formula adopted by many movie trailers over the years:  For real? Forget you‚Äôre a Marvel fanboy for a minute and remember that Old-school music paired with high-octane action did exist before Guardians of The Galaxy. Come on now...  And finally: For those who are calling it ‚ÄúBad‚Äù before even seeing it:  Either give it a chance before basing your judgments on two minutes and thirty seconds of the film, or keep your cancerous options to yourself. text: First of all, being a Comic Artist, I just LOVE Hellboy, and love all comic dark side. In Del Toro movie seems great for me, because I love fairy creatures and monsters and stuff like that...  even if it was different tone from the Comic. I was really disappointed when del Toro said there will not be 3rd movie of this franchise, that have great potential and can do spectacular films.  Now I see this trailer... I m confused. I like Harbour... I like HellBoy aspect... different from previous two. But, little perplexity about the STORY... I can see only on the trailer guns and like any stupid action movie the SAME PROCEDURE : A cynic guy with a gun, making some 'kidding' in worst moments... He is big and huge and look fierce, and other minimal characters around that does not have any sentiment... the just speak and move...  VERY FAST SCENES with lots of BANG BANG...  Mila Jovovich is not my favorite evil... and she is dressed in a stupid way ( does not look fierce or evil )  I expected slower scenes, real monsters and DARK creatures... being fascinated and feel fear, anxiety, surprise...  it does not happen with the trailer... hm. Sorry guys... I m real Hellboy fun... I hope the movie will be better !!! Even with low budget... EMOTIONS are what we expect from a film !!!  ( in HellBoy II he expected twins from his fiancee... so... what about that ???!!! The Death make them give a promise... I wait for the sequel...)

text: You know... If people would simply STOP going to see shitty remakes and reboots, maybe...just maybe Hollywood might start to make original stuff again. Complaining about it on Youtube won't change anything though.  Here; you want something different, funny, scary, sad, and triumphant? Here is a link to a Gofund me page and an accompanying Facebook page belonging to a disabled person who is trying to make something awesome. He has already had 2 academy award nominees read it and state that his story is a masterful work of comedic genius wrapped in a Lord of the Rings type universe where cannabis is a sacred herb used to enlighten.  This story makes fun of stupid social trends, certain idiotic politicians and celebrities, and asks us all to NOT judge a book by its cover. It is destined to be a classic and/or cult masterpiece. It is loaded with political and social satire and pokes fun at EVERYONE in hopes that we will all see how ridiculous we all can be. It is a great read that WILL make you want to see a movie about it. It WILL make you cry and laugh.  It has trolls. goblins, elves, dragons, and an assortment of classical fantasy species and some that you have never heard of before. Imagine Billy Crystal as a pot-smoking gnome who is also a holy man and a wizard and who is hoping to reintroduce his people to their creator and god through the use of cannabis. He enlists the aid of a Sasquatch comedian (who Dan Aykroyd expressed interest in playing), a nightmarish warlord battle-master thing, a giant lizardman, a bipedal rodent-like creature, and a being whose story is a mystery in itself.  The laughs are intense as are the tears and the elation of victory when it happens.  It is unbelievable that people will dish out $200,000 to a porn star rolling in money so she can sue her john, but they won't support someone who is honest, hard-working, and actually has something to offer the world. Terrible to say the least. This guy doesn't need $200,000 he is only trying to drum up $8,500 to publish his work so he will have something tangible to send to Peter Jackson, and Adam Macay (his fav directors).  Help the guy out, he is disabled and hates being on a disability pension. It has taken over 30 years to perfect this epic trilogy, over 320,000 words long. Self-sufficiency is all he wants (and to leave his son something when he passes away), and his work is brilliant. He is not lazy and has worked extremely long and hard to make this modern-day answer to The Lord Of The Rings meets Cheech and Chong.  https://www.gofundme.com/self-publishing-book-fund  https://m.facebook.com/The-Adventures-of-the-Great-Neblinski-by-JRR-Tokin-1774047899272119/?refid=13&__tn__=%2Cg

text: Guess I'm in minority here but I really dig the trailer. I feel like it does a pretty good job establishing itself as it's own beast which it should. Hellboy 3 is dead it's sad but true, but I'm happy we're even getting a Hellboy movie at all. I think David Harbour is doing a fine job in his role and will come into his own as the movie progresses. I also actually like his makeup. Feels different enough to stand on it's own and it's kinda like a hybrid of the comic and the Del Toro version.  Other things to keep in mind.   1) Hellboy is a lot younger in this movie and less refined. Hes just trying to find himself.  2) This movie is low budget due to the R rating. Studios hate giving money to R rated properties because it cuts out a huge demographic that goes to see movies. Same thing happened with the first Deadpool.  3) Neil Marshall Is a kickass director. Watch The Descent and Dog Soldiers. Some fantastic gore, creatures, scares and humor in those. (Well humor in dog soldiers since it's a horror comedy)  4) Mike Mignola the creator of Hellboy is extremely excited about this version. He worked closely with them and loves what they are doing and hopes it does well so they can adapt his favorite stories. It actually follows closer to the Hellboy mythos and comics than the Del Toro ones. At least according to Mignola.  But look I do honestly get it. Hellboy is in my top 5 favorite movies of all time. I love it with my heart and soul. Change sucks and it's scary. But I wouldn't count this one out yet. And if does well it could kickstart a Hellboy series which would be fucking amazing. Just my two cents.

text: Couple things: The director, Neil Marshall. He did Dog Soldiers, The Descent, and Doomsday. He also directed a few of the most exciting and action-packed episodes of GoT in the series: (The Battle of Blackwater, The Seige on the Wall, etc.) There WILL be gore. There WILL be great action. There WILL be a lot of things we're not yet seeing, because they're R-rated. Hellboy has always been one to make little quips and silly jokes, while terrible, DARK, and GRITTY things are happening all around him. The creator, Mike Mignola, was very involved with this production, including writing and producing. There are already many MANY things in this trailer which should get a true Hellboy fan excited. Especially if you've been keeping up with the comics. Obviously, it doesn't look or feel like Del Toro's movies, because it's not supposed to!  To be fair, I would have gone with any other music choice for this trailer.  Give it a chance before you completely dismiss it.

text: I REALLY miss The King Ron Pearlman. BUT I'm also going to watch this anyway "just for the hell of it" there's been a hell of drought since no trilogy was in sight. I'm just happy to see someone trying again. But they really should've just harassed TF out of Guillermo to do a third. I hope it's darker than this trailer let's on. I really do. First thing I noticed was that the old Hellboy 1 and 2 cgi looked better than this extremely noticeable difference. I think the old had more practical effects which would make sense. Going full CGI instead of a great balance with reality is what's killing the scare factor of monsters. The animated ones in a real world without the right budget or animators feels so fucking weightless regardless of all the loud noises and shaky cams you put when it slams into something. And Mila..... Fucking really? Come on man. Resident Evil going so far down hill into even more goofy than the over the top franchise going into that realm with bad choreography in fights ripped straight from the game and just a shoddy use of CGI. Why would you inject her into this to? Her role in that never showcased any amazing acting since 3 onward I can't remember a stellar performance. So again. Fucking why? I'm gonna assume the reason we have no Ron is because it's not Guillermo or the same world.

text: So why are we upset? Ok they reboot Helloby instead of making a 3rd one, why? Because the 2nd (which was far better than the first one) didnt succeed finacially and a 3rd one would "only" have served a small fanbase, so the studios cancelled it.  Its the old dilemma between creativity versus making money. I think a lot of directors could do better if their creativity wouldnt be surpressed by the financial interests of the studios. Why does every film looks the same these days? Especially the super hero films? Because the studios have a pretty save formular of generating money. Its the style of Guillermo del Toro which makes us want to have a 3rd Hellboy. He creates a vivid and creative Hellboy-universe and therefor he sets the bar high. So they may getting 100% more viewers because of that formular but 50% will be dissapointed because it looks mainstream.

text: I'm willing to give it a chance. I love the Del Toro movies and while sad he won't be making the 3rd installment I think this still has some chance. I think Harbour's Hellboy gives us something close enough to Perlman's rendition to help with nostalgia and not jarr fans of the first movies, but it's different enough to give it his own vibe. Even Harbour himself said in an interview, that he's aware at how big the shoes he has to fill are, in regards to replacing Perlman in this role. I'm mostly curious about his interactions with Mila's character and that scene of him coming out of that hole with his full horns, flame crown and flaming sword. That part gave me some chills knowing how much others are interested in using him and his right hand for all the dark shit it's made for. I'm curious as to where this movie will take us. text: I‚Äôve been noticing a lot of negative comments on this trailer, so I‚Äôd like to make a little PSA about the subject.  As someone who‚Äôs watched (and loved) both of Del Toro and Ron Pearlman‚Äôs Hellboy films, I know how nostalgia and rose tinted glasses can make a great trailer like this seem ‚Äúdisrespectful.‚Äù I understand that the filmmakers have promised a gritty and darker Hellboy film, and we will get it, but that‚Äôs not what we‚Äôre being shown here.  Hellboy, despite being rooted in horror, also had a lot of humor, and that‚Äôs what we‚Äôre being shown here. In fact, looking back on the filmmakers interviews about it, they said that this Hellboy would be a monster flick rather then a superhero film.  So guys, let‚Äôs all keep our minds clear of bias and judge this movie for what it is, and not what it‚Äôs supposed to be. I know that a lot of you will despise this film because it ‚Äúisn‚Äôt Del Toro‚Äù, but if we say that then this film won‚Äôt be what it was intended to be.   So let‚Äôs be opened minded and view this Hellboy movie as bias free as possible.

text: I'm iffy on the makeup, but it's really not _that_ far from Perlman's.  He looks very similar.  Except this Hellboy's face seems a lot... lumpier.  I'm going to have to give the makeup to Perlman's.  Although this Hellboy's crown looks very cool.  Harbour's voice doesn't have quite the expressiveness of Perlman's, and sounds a bit slushy.  I've seen it suggested below it's because of the makeup.  But his voice doesn't carry well when he's shouting, like when he got out of the cop van.  Speaking of getting out of the cop van... please drop that stupid stupid stupid "my bad" joke from the 90's.  Seriously.  Rewrite that scene.  Now.  Now.  Now.  Anyway, I still see a lot of the Hellboy character that Perlman portrayed in what Harbour is portraying.  We can't expect them to be identical.  And the makers of this movie made a good choice:  it's not a reboot.  The character isn't being reintroduced.  It takes place after the original movies.  So we aren't going to see Hellboy Reboot #234.  Perlman's portrayal of Hellboy was brilliant.  It will be difficult to top it.  But I'm willing to give this movie, and Harbour, a fair shake.  As long as the rest of the lines aren't like "My bad".

text: There is alot of unnecessary hate for this it seems, I agree the trailer could have been better but it definitely doesn't fully define the movie as a whole. I am sure we all remember thinking suicide squad looked epic from the trailer, but the movie..something else.  I would like to point out that a lot of people are saying it looks too comedic but even in the Comics Hellboy has humour and I think people are forgetting that the del Toro films had a large amount of humour to them.  For example Hellboy and Abe sitting in front of a fire getting drunk singing I can't live without you or Hellboy getting his face bounced off locker doors by a German steam geist.  A lot of people have said that his voice should be more deeper/ demonic as well but Ron Perlmans voice was his own, no deeper. Just slightly muffled at times from prosthetics.  I Love the original hellboy's but I am all for a new Direction that is closer to the comics and even though the trailer has a odd choice of soundtrack to it .I am more than willing to give this a chance because I think it has potential to be fantastic especially with the Creator so heavily involved.  Respect and love to you all

text: Comment section in a nutshell: "Change is bad! I hate change! I only want what I'm used to! I only want actors that that give me nostalgia boners! New is never good, always bad! Ron Perlman, Ron Perlman, Ron Perlman, Ron Perlman, Ron Perlman, and on and on..."   I saw the original Hellboy and the 2nd one a few times and they were okay. Not too exiting, but the acting was good. This new one looks fun to me. I like the actors, their enthusiasm, and the lines seem suited to a comic book that's meant to be dark, but also have some humor. And let's put it this way, I'd much rather see this than the new MIB movie. I'm not saying it'll be bad. One can't make a complete judgement based on trailers. However, it didn't get me excited for it. More confused than anything else. Hellboy, at least, looks like it'll make me laugh a few times.

text: no Ron Perlman.  i wont see this because of that. its not that im really a hardcore fan of Ron. But, when you change superhero's actors. the tone and feel of the character is changed dramatically.  What if The guy who plated Logan from the X-men, Hugh Jackman was replaced with leonardo dicaprio. the feel of the character. would be horrible. Ron got his role for the way he FITs the role, attitude, and feel. I understand what happen with Spiderman. but what happen really lowered the expectations of what the character that plays Spider man would be. When we see Tobey Maguire, we think. Spiderman. great acting. and a role that we can relate to and feel comfortable with. but when it was taken over by Tom Holland, the feel of the character seamed less confident, was more "green" (lack in fast thinking due to a lack of experience.) and the general script he is given doesnt seam very spider-man like. The swap from the 3 hulks where ... meanial. Eric Bana to Edward Norton to Mark Ruffalo. this wasnt because there was problems with the actors, but because the Hulk's Bruce David Banner was to be portray as a time lapse section. someone with incredible stress and and worry. it was to show the audience how such a thing changes people. and finally. Ryan Reynolds. He played as green lantern first. but then was made into Deadpool. why is this? well. Green Lantern wasnt a very fitting character for Ryan. at all. but. Deadpool was. Ryan and his advanced Sarcasm fit the character spot on. and now we cant see Deadpool as anyone but Ryan. and like wise. Stan Lee agreed to cut out the Green Lantern from history. and even had thoughts of rebooting it from square one. But. R.I.P. Stan Lee.

text: Now don't get me wrong, I was stoked when I heard when that they were making a third Hellboy. Granted, I was a disappointed that Perlman was not going to be in this one. However when I heard Harbour was casted, I had high hopes that he'd pull this off well.  But by the trailer, it seems like they're tryna pull some Guardians humor which isn't bad if done well (and so far it's not looking good). Secondly, the makeup and prosthetics look horrendous (for Hellboy especially), just overall botox. And lastly, the CGI looks as if it's made for a movie that was made by the SYFY channel. Now, this is only the trailer and I will see the movie when released to get a much better perspective. But so far I'm not feeling quite confident.

text: The whole trailer is ripped almost straight from the comics and as far as i can tell it looks really great for anyone who has read the comic and like utter shit to everyone else.    Which kinda is the big problem with this movie. Very few people actually know the source material when it comes to Hellboy. So everyone just expects it to be a whole different movie and on top of that are pissed at Hollywood rebooting another fan-favourite franchise.    But at least to me - big hellboy fan, comics as well as the movies - the trailer looks like it could be the adaption of the comics I always wanted, but never got to see, since Del Toro has such a strong directing style which overrode a lot of the comics influence. Don't get me wrong the movies are great and Ron Perlman is the best, but they never really captured the same feel I got when reading the comics.     I just hope for a good movie and I actually think a Hellboy reboot has a lot to offer if done right, but I fear it will go down like DREDD. An amazing genre movie, almost perfect adaption wise, but nobody turned out to see it, because they expect a redo of the original movie instead of a fresh start.     Or everyone is right and it turns out to be shit. Guess we'll see.

text: What you idiots fail to realize is that the Ron Perlman Hellboys were based loosely on the comics! That's why they we're only rated PG-13! Now that they are sticking more to the comics of course it's going to be darker and rated R! How many of you have actually read the comics? I'm actually glad that they went with someone else. If you've read the comics you would know that the comics book version of Hellboys isn't as built as Ron was in the movies. The comic book version of Hellboy actually had skinny as arms. I'm glad that they decided not to make a cookie cutter reboot of Hellboy. So instead of bitching about something that isn't even out yet, wait, go watch the movie, then give your opinion. text: man this comment section is so divided, on one side we have nostalgia and on the other the comic people (for my own laughter I'll call them commies).  truth about this movie from what I've seen in this trailer is this. the CGI is lacking in the trailer, it looks like they made it decent then called it a day, the actor sounds fine but the make up, yeesh. why does it look like he has straight botox across his whole face, makes me nauseous. but I'll hold out hope since it is closer to the source material. as for the OGs, they weren't as good as the comment section is making them out to be, but the commies are wrong if they say they were trash. for their time the practical make up and effects were pretty solid and the CGI is comparable to this one's (which is sad). while the acting was solid the directing was questionable during certain scenes and honestly felt entirely different from the comics.  so in conclusion, the previous ones were ok movies, and this new one had my interest.  but jesus, that fuckin face

I wanted to see Del Toro finish his trilogy, but that wasnt an option unfortunately. The studio wouldnt let it happen. So it was this or nothing. And honestly, this looks pretty good even when comparing it to the Del Toro films. Better? Eh, maybe not. But I'm more than willing to give it a chance. text: Change Hellboy into a Action Adventure "Horror" Love Dramedy Story. Alice Monaghan is not a BPRD Agent that knows Kungfu, she's Hellboys Girlfriend.  The comedy between Ben Daimio and Hellboy needs to be reshot and revised, it's not funny enough. Or it's been mishandled.  Ian MacShanes character needs to be a dream sequence not a father who is still alive...  Hellboy needs to be depicted as an adult, with a past that haunts him, and not like this "angsty" "teenager" crap you gave us.  All the R rated stuff can still be in it, but the trailer ruined a lot of the audience expectations for this film. This 3rd Hellboy movie was supposed to have the same emotional weight that the previous 2 Hellboy movies provided. Revise the Swat Scene shown in the trailer, make it more serious, but passively comedic in tone. Like the violent humor displayed in Kong Skull Island   LionsGate still has time to revise this film so that there are no cringey fight scenes and dialogue between characters.  Unless of course the movie is considered finished and there's no way to go back and save these scenes... Then release a different trailer that has a different tone¬† that proves there is an emotional weight to this Hellboy story and then publicly release it to IGN and this LionsGate channel  Yeah sure the official trailer ruined expectations but there is gotta be a way to help the public view.

text: honestly i have a lot of faith in the movie. i was at the NYCC panel where Mike Mignola and the cast were there and they had a special preview screening. i‚Äôve been thrilled for the film since.   the fact that Mike Mignola (the creator of Hellboy) spoke so highly of this film and was a huge part in its creation (writing & how it follows one of the actual Hellboy comics, whereas the Del Toro films strayed from the original material) makes me believe it is going to be awesome.   don‚Äôt get me wrong, Ron Perlman‚Äôs portrayal and Del Toro‚Äôs movies were amazing (and the new cast were sure to express that as well during the panel), but this should be respected as a separate art.   this is a different telling of Hellboy (a younger, more gritty - following much closer to horror, which is more true to the comics) and that isn‚Äôt a bad thing.  if you like Hellboy, MIKE MIGNOLA‚ÄôS TRUE HELLBOY, i know you‚Äôll enjoy the film. mike said it himself and i trust his word.   if you can‚Äôt seem to get past Del Toro‚Äôs Hellboy and that‚Äôs your only exposure to Hellboy, then i can get why you‚Äôre being so dramatic. but get over it, lol. this is just the trailer. the movie has a lot more in store for us.

text: I don't agree with all of the hate this trailer is getting. All of the criticisms I've heard range from it being a rip-off of Deadpool (I guess because there are some jokes in there), that there's no way David Harbour can fill Ron Perlman's shoes, etc. The only valid criticism I've heard is that most people wanted a sequel, not a complete remake. I can certainly get on board with that criticism, but to not have even seen the movie and to write off David Harbour's performance right off the bat reminds me of, well, butt-hurt teenage, diehard DC fans. You know the type of fan to make multiple fake accounts to vote 0 stars for movies they want to tank? The type to vote either 0 or 5 stars and nothing in between because all they care about is for "their team" (what a stupid concept) to win.

If you were an original content creator, not just piggybacking off other's content, then you'd be fine with these copyright laws, however, this guy is a critic without having the rights or credentials that critics do. He isn't provided the film to review, he's reviewing a trailer, sharing copyrighted content. A low budget film company has the right to do claim what they own, as does anyone else. Just because it's impacting your YouTube channel (and some fans) doesn't mean you're right and the laws are wrong. Make your own damn movie if you have talent!

text: I am surprised by the comments. I am always a hardass on movies. When everyone loves them I think they're shit. While I do agree this trailer tried to fit in with the other witty super hero flicks, I didn't think it looked bad past all that added fluff. They definitely should have went gritty with the trailer. But I like the costume. Much better than the first movie. It looks far less cartoony. It blends in more. And I think the awful delivered humor can work for Hellboy. Hellboy tries to hide his turmoil behind his humor. It's a shield. He's not good at it. I think too many of you are attempting to compare it to the original movies. Stop. Don't. This isn't a remake it is a reboot.

I think they‚Äôve gotten the nose and the eye areas perfect. He‚Äôs also a darker color than he was in the Del Toro movies. And he‚Äôs not shiny anymore!  The music was definitely not a great choice, but if you actually look at some of these shots and think about how they might play into the movie, it seems to be appropriately dark. And terms of that, let‚Äôs not pretend that the old movies captured the atmosphere OR characters from the comics. Ron Perlman was fantastic, but he wasn‚Äôt entirely true to the comics. Not that that really matters.  The thing that I find strange is that Daimio is in this movie for some reason. He‚Äôs an odd character choice, and his casting is just... no. But I‚Äôm actually super fucking excited for this movie. I think it looks amazing.

text: As a fan of Hellboy and the first two films this did not catch my interest.  Here's the issue. Instead of carving out it's own identity it's just trying to be something else, and it's taking the lazy appoach by just copying what's Marvels schtick. I shouldn't be getting GOTG/Ant-Man/Spiderman:HC vibes from a source material like this.  The R rated aspect is really great since there isn't may R rated superhero flicks but instead of going deeping into something like that, they slapped on humor just because it's easily "lucrative". Meanwhile you have things like Logan and WW trying to be great films in their own right with their own identity and look at that they were huge hits cause of it.  Please stop trying to copy Marvel, like Dwayne Johnson said, stop trying to be the next Marvel and be the first you(or whatever he says in that trailer...). Look at the reception of SS and JL. text: meh.  Despite the apparent decent sized fanbase.... I'm guessing Hellboy has gained a cult following.... I'm guessing this movie does about as well as the original.... BARELY making it's money back.  First film had a production budget of $66M and made only $99M at the box office.  How this has become a series and NOW a reboot is baffling.  Hellboy 2 must've done stellar at the box office, right, to garner a reboot?  Not really.  $160.5M on an $85M budget?  It made a little money, but hardly enough to warrant a reboot.  But this is Hollywood now.  If it isn't a comic book movie it's a sequel.... if it's not a sequel it's a reboot.  In this case it's a rebooted comic book movie.  And the brain dead media wonder why movie ticket sales continue to dwindle with each passing year.  Hollywood is about as original as Milli Vanilli nowadays.  I can't remember the last time I saw a trailer and said "DAMN, I absolutely HAVE to go see that."  It's been MANY years I can tell you that.   AH... just thought of probably the last film I said "I must see that."  Inglorious Basterds.  That movie is a decade old already.... damn.

Yes we all probably really wanted to see what was going to happen with Ron Pearlman's hellboy story arc, however perhaps if this does follow the comics, that huh have an audience, then maybe it will also entertain as well as those comics do. 2:30 seconds aint gonna tell you much others than faces and the general plot, like it's a super hero fantasy movie, are any of you expecting a plot twist that will blow your brains out the back of your head or a story so rich and deep that it makes game of thrones look like child's play? like not sure why so much bashing, it looks fun, maybe a little too much deadpool-type fun in the trailer, but hopefully it's a hellboy movie and not another we have to be a funny hero now movie.

text: After watching the cartoon version at least 3 times, I'm not totally sure about this whole live-action thing, kinda seems like a trend recently, like wut Disney's been do'n. Hellboy in the trailer didn't feel quite right to me. In the cartoon movie, Blood & Iron. 1. He's more of the quiet type. 2. He *CAN* have fun and have funny moments, but since he's more of the quiet type, the funny is more in his actions, like when he thinks he's got it right and then figures out he got it wrong. 3. He's actually smart and level headed as well in many situations. And when he says, "It smashes real good", you already know he got knocked down a peg. How the characters look are actually pretty good, they look fine, but it's really in the acting and how good the ppl play their parts that'll determine whether or not this movie is worth going to in my opinion. When this gets in theaters, it doesn't look bad, it just kinda feels bad from the trailer, but we should give it a chance at the very least before really digging into it and calling it rlly bad, even though it's just the trailer. But since Cpt. Marvel was so bad in terms of how ppl were "advertising" it, les hope tht we don't go down that HELL-hole (get it, cuz the... Never mind) again. So, chances are, if ppl don't like it when it comes out in theaters, then that's fine, everybody has their opinion on the movie. But, the more ppl who say it's good, the more ppl will watch it, but if ppl say it's not rlly worth spending yr money on, then much less ppl will be inclined to go watch it. Word spreads like a wild fire, you won't know how it'll end. :P

text: I loved this movie.  It's not as good as the original, but I liked it better than part II.  I always felt The Golden Army was alright, but a lot lighter in tone and too silly when compared to the original.  I wasn't looking forward to seeing "mommy and daddy" Liz and Hellboy raising two hellboy babies, either.  This movie was a completely different take for the character.  They stayed away from using characters and situations that we'd already seen in the previous movies to keep things fresh.  I actually prefer Hellboy's look in this film.  The crimson flesh color looks a lot better than the bright red color from the original films and I never liked Hellboy's bald head, either.  Overall, the look of Hellboy fits the character a lot better in this film.  There are also some very interesting situations that Hellboy finds himself in, that are only hinted at in the old series, but are explored a lot more in this film.  If you can set aside your grudge that Hellboy 3 was probably never going to happen and you're willing to see a grittier take on the character and source material, with as much stuff from the comics as they could throw in there, you'll enjoy the movie for what it is.  The saddest thing is that the 2 after credit scenes gave a glimpse of some awesome things that were to come in the sequel and now we'll probably never see that film become a reality, either.

text: No offence to everyone but I thought this was WAY better than the original...... It looked like actual hell near the end, the massive disgusting torturous creatures and the human killings were just next level in comparison to the original... It made the original look PG..... Look I liked the original too, it was pretty awesome! However, if this was the original, could you imagine the crazy, disgusting, bizarre films that would have followed? Definitely would surpass that of the originals. The humour to me did not feel forced if anything I thought he suited that role perfectly! His face was ugly, he just looked far more "hellish"...  I was actually disappointed hearing about the replacement and a new Hellboy etc... However, these guys did a fucking fantastic job! I hope they make another.  Finally, Hellboy being summoned to places that Hellboy would actually belong. Demented horrors with children stew... Not cigars over a desk chasing a girlfriend...................  Great job Lionsgate!

He sounds like a little kid trying to talk with a cheap, thick halloween mask on ... while wearing a mouth guard.  Way to lie and disappoint your fans Perlman. I'm going to have to go back and re-watch the episode of SOA where Jax takes Perlman out again just to make me feel a little better.
